Part I - Airline Delays and Cancellations Causes and Statistics¶

by Basel Zayyat¶

Introduction¶

The complete data set consists of flight arrival and departure details for all commercial flights within the USA, from October 1987 to April 2008.
As the original dataset is ~120MM records and for the purposes of the analysis, this analysis will be limited to 3 years (1988,1998, and 2008).
The choice of the years considered a systematic sample where an interval of 10 years was chosen to represent the population.
The data was downloaded from the American Statistical Association from here
where the original data set is collected by The data is collected by the Office of Airline Information, Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS), United States Department of Transportation. The original data set can be found here
The chosen sample contains 17,596,545 rows and represents ~ 15% of the total available data set with 29 columns explained in the below table:

The aim of this study is to better understand the attributes contributing to delays and cancellations of flights. for the purposes of this study a flight is considered delayed when it is 15 minutes later than its scheduled time and cancellation occurs when the airline does not operate the flight at all for a certain reason as per the The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA), details can be found here

The sample dataset was further reduced into a subset that captures delays equal to or greater than 15 minutes and cancelled flights generating 4,400,236 rows and 29 columns for the analysis. This subset was saved as 'd_c_flights.csv'

What are the top 10 carriers in terms of delays or cancellations?¶

In [18]:
#generate plot data

plt_data = flights['UniqueCarrier'].value_counts().head(10)
plt_order = plt_data.index

#adjust color

colors = c_palette[0]

#define plot 

plt.subplots(figsize=(7,7))
plt.rcParams.update({'axes.xmargin': 0.5})
ax = sns.countplot(data=flights,x='UniqueCarrier',color = colors, order=plt_order)

#set title and axis

plt.title('Delays and Cancellation by Carrier - Top 10', fontsize=16);
plt.xlabel('Carrier Airline Code', fontsize=14);
plt.ylabel('Total number of delays for the years 88, 98, 08 \n(15 minutes or more) or cancellations', 
           fontsize=14);

#add values to bars

for p in ax.patches:
   ax.annotate('{:}'.format(p.get_height()), (p.get_x()+0.25, p.get_height()+0.03), rotation = 90,
              color = 'white', horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top',
              size=14)

#display plot

plt.show()

Southwest seems to have suffered the largest numbers of delays with United Airlines, American Airlines, and Delta right after

How does air time affect delays?¶

Airtime 50 minutes or less seem to suffer the bulk of the delays indicating that shorter flights are more likely to suffer delays

Bivariate Exploration¶

Do departure delays have an effect on arrival delays?¶

In [30]:
#generate plot data

plt_data = flights[(flights['Cancelled']== 0) & 
                   ((flights['DepDelay'] != 0) | 
                   ( flights['ArrDelay']!=0))]

#generate plot

plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
plt.scatter(data=plt_data,x='DepDelay',y='ArrDelay',alpha=1/20);

#calculate the trendline

fit = np.polyfit(plt_data['DepDelay'], plt_data['ArrDelay'], 1)
poly_line = np.poly1d(fit)

#print trend line

plt.plot(plt_data['DepDelay'],plt_data['DepDelay'],"r-");

#set title and axis

plt.title('Departures vs. Arrivals Delays (minutes) \n for the years 88, 98, 08', fontsize=16);
plt.xlabel('Departure Delay (minutes)', fontsize=14);
plt.ylabel('Arrival Delay (minutes)', fontsize=14);

#refocus axes to delay >= 15 minutes as pre definition

plt.xlim(14,);
plt.ylim(14,);

#show plot

plt.show();
print('Pearson correlation coefficient: ',stats.pearsonr(plt_data.DepDelay, plt_data.ArrDelay)[0]);

Pearson correlation coefficient:  0.8452848794503204

a linear relationship is observed between departure delays and arrival delays as expected

Conclusions¶

Multiple delay and cancellation factors were explored. However, it is to be noted that the chosen subset only included delayed and cancelled flights and not the full flight data set due to system limitations, hence, the findings are limited to the study subset of cancelled and delayed flights and could present a biased view. The study subset is also assumed to represent and model the behaviour of over 3 decades of flying through the selection of the years 1988, 1998, and 2008 as a representative selective sample.

The univariate exploration included relationships between :¶

  1. Carriers and the total number of delays/cancellations: for the study period, during which it was observed that the worst three carriers in terms of the numbers of cancellations are Southwest, United Airlines and American Airlines
  2. Airports and the total number of delays/cancellations: through which it was established that flights departing from or landing into Orlando are more likely to suffer from delays or cancellations
  3. _Day of the week, day of the month, scheduled departure time, and scheduled arrival time :_Fridays, day 22 of the month and departing between 4 to 7 PM or landing between 7 to 9 PM a traveller is more likely to suffer from delays or cancellations
  4. Cancellation by code:Cancellation by Carrier and National Aviation System (non-extreme weather conditions, airport operations, heavy traffic volume, and air traffic control) are the top two reasons for flight cancellations
  5. Airtime and delays: flights shorter than 50 minutes of Air Time are more likely to experience delays or cancellation
  6. Tail number / flight number and total number of cancellations: United Airline appears to take the top 10 spots in terms of total delays and cancellations grouped by tail number with flight numbers 419, 65 and 343 suffering above average delays and cancellations.

The bivariate exploration included relationships between :¶

  1. Scheduled departure time and scheduled arrival time: for which a linear relationship was observed were a delay on one side causes a delay on the other.
  2. Scheduled arrival delays and Airtime: were it was observed that plans are able to recover delays as air time increases
  3. Taxi out time vs. departure delay and taxi in time vs. arrival delay: delayed departures received preference in terms of taxi timings while this preference was not provided on arrival as a taxi in preference.

The multivariate exploration included relationships between :¶

  1. Month, day of the month and mean delays: July the 13th pops as the day of highest mean delays.
  2. Month, day of the week and mean delays: July Sunday's has the max mean delays
  3. Month, day of the month and total cancellations: July 1 has had the most cancellations over the study period
  4. Month, day of the week and total cancellations: January Thursday's appear to suffer the highest number of cancellatoins
  5. Month, scheduled departure time, total delays(departure/arrival max): 16:00 to 19:00 appears to be the period being hit the hradest with delays, with red eye flights showing better performance
